We next turn our attention to 2DES, through which the coherent17 and incoherent16 dynamics of excited states can be monitored. In this technique, details of which can be found elsewhere49,50, a material interacts with four ultrashort laser pulses, which can be grouped into an initial “excitation” pair and a subsequent “detection” pair, and the resulting signal is commonly presented as an excitation–detection correlation spectrum for each time delay between the two pulse pairs. Different combinations of pulse interactions result in different spectral signals. In our aim to interpret recent experiments on TMDCs23, we specifically focus on the non-rephasing stimulated emission signal,3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
