				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$S(\omega _1,t_2,\omega _3) =	 - (\frac{{2\pi }}{\hbar })^2\mathop {\sum}\limits_{\alpha ,\beta } {\left| {\left\langle {\Psi ^{\mathrm{i}}} \right|V\left| {\Psi ^\alpha } \right\rangle } \right|^2} \left| {\left\langle {\Psi ^{\mathrm{i}}} \right|V\left| {\Psi ^\beta } \right\rangle } \right|^2\\ 	\times e^{ - (i\omega _{\alpha \beta } + \gamma _{\alpha \beta })t_2}\Gamma ^ \ast (E^\alpha - E^{\mathrm{i}} - \hbar \omega _1)\Gamma (E^\beta - E^{\mathrm{i}} - \hbar \omega _3).$$\end{document}S(ω1,t2,ω3)=-(2πℏ)2 ∑α,βΨiVΨα2ΨiVΨβ2×e-(iωαβ+γαβ)t2Γ*(Eα-Ei-ℏω1)Γ(Eβ-Ei-ℏω3).Here, ω1 and ω3 are the excitation and detection energies, respectively, and t2 is the time delay. The complex lineshape function is given by Γ(ω) = 1/(iω − σ), with σ as the linebroadening parameter. The excitation energy difference between excited states α and β is given by ωαβ = (Eα − Eβ)/ℏ and γαβ represents the associated decoherence rate. The most important mechanistic origin of decoherence is believed to be the scattering of quasiparticles with lattice phonons, and a microscopic investigation of this phenomenon is an interesting topic for future research, albeit beyond the scope of the present study. The damped oscillation as a function of the time delay (quantum beat) contained in the exponential is mapped onto the 2DES signal weighted by the product of transition matrix elements between the excited states and a common initial state Ψi. In particular, excited states that do not share a common initial state, as might arise in inhomogeneous samples, do not show coherent cross-peaks in 2DES.

